A system of favoritism capitalism à la américaine
Do you remember the East Asian crisis? When the U.S. Treasury and its IMF allies shifted the blame for the problems in this region onto a system of favoritism capitalism, lack of transparency, and an ineffective government?
The countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting firms, and to introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their businesses.
It makes no difference that under the authority of its own entrepreneurs, East Asia has developed more rapidly than any other region—and with greater stability—over the past three decades.
The growing scandal of Enron gives new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "You must be without fault to criticize others."
Enron used large accounting schemes and complex financial products (derivatives) to mislead investors about its value.
No transparency here.
She used her money to gain influence and power, shape U.S. energy policy, and avoid regulations.
Favoritism capitalism is not new, nor is it the exclusive domain of a single party.
The former U.S. Treasury Secretary, Robert Rubin, would have tried to influence the current government to intervene on Enron's behalf in the controversial dispute in India.
When he was in office, he intervened when the accounting standards-setting body, supposedly independent, attempted to clean up the accounting of top executives' stock transactions.
It was in part due to him that this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent was hindered.
The enthusiasm of America to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free markets is merely a thin veil for the welfare of old companies: giving favors to those who have good connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and the issues were not revealed demonstrates the absence of favoritism capitalism.
My interpretation is different: it demonstrates the importance of a free press that may not stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to investigate Enron, the number of members of Congress who had accepted money from Enron was disclosed.
Contributions to campaigns were not merely a matter of public interest, but an investment.
Like most Enron investments, everything went smoothly in the short term, but yielded no results in the long term.
Several lessons can be drawn from this company.
Some related to policy: the Enron scandal strengthens the arguments in favor of campaign finance reform and the necessity for even more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
Democracies are undermined by corporate interests that are in fact capable of buying elections.
The Bush administration refuses, however, to disclose information that would attest to the role of corporate interests in shaping its energy policy.
Other lessons pertain to the economy, more specifically the information economy.
For the markets to function, for the appropriate signals aimed at efficiently allocating resources to be provided, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as rosy a picture as possible.
Accounting controls are intended to place limits on potential abuses.
But who will guard the guardians?
Who will control the accountants' controllers?
We count greatly on the motivations.
The auditors wish to preserve their reputation.
But the relationship between consulting practices and accounting controls brings about other corrupted motivations: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within the accounting audit firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of the controls could be compromised.
He is undoubtedly the forgotten hero of the collapse.
But accounting audit firms and their corporate clients—nothing surprising, given the collusion that has developed—strongly attacked his proposal to separate consulting and accounting control activities.
What Levitt understood—and the Enron collapse so clearly demonstrated—is that motivations matter, but that unregulated markets cannot on their own provide the best motivations.
Markets cannot provide motivations for the creation of wealth; they can provide motivations for the type of schemes that Enron was implementing.
The new economy—and its complex new financial instruments—highlight the problems with reliable accounting control structures; they make them easier to confuse.
Rather than confronting the problems, the corporate America systematically turns its back on them, supported and encouraged by the American-style favoritism capitalism.
The major problem of our time is to find the proper balance between government and the market.
The status quo will claim that Enron was an exception: that its collapse was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud, and that those who violate these laws must face the consequences and will face them.
But the majority of Enron's actions were legal.
His auditors claim that its core practices complied with the law and that thousands of companies act the same way.
They are right—and that is precisely the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information they receive adequately reflects the economic situation of a company.
Within the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors have no possibility of being offered these guarantees at the present time.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check the motivations.
We can try to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot rely on them when so many people around the world say nothing about the phenomenon of the "revolving door."
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we see that they can manage them for their own interests.
But even when evidence of such abuses becomes evident, new sites of abuse are repeatedly created—take the U.S. repeal of the Glass-Steagall Act, which separated commercial from investment banking.
We have repeatedly observed the consequences of the excesses of unregulated market liberalization.
We must now resist the temptation to lean toward the other extreme.
The challenge is to achieve the right balance.
